404. Drugs. 2015 Feb;75(2):207-17. doi: 10.1007/s40265-014-0344-z.

Silodosin: a review of its use in the treatment of the signs and symptoms of 
benign prostatic hyperplasia.

Keating GM(1).

Author information:
(1)Springer, Private Bag 65901, Mairangi Bay 0754, Auckland, New Zealand, 
demail@springer.com.

Silodosin is a highly selective α1A-adrenoceptor antagonist indicated for the 
treatment of the signs and symptoms of benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH). Oral 
silodosin had a rapid onset of effect in men with lower urinary tract symptoms 
(LUTS) associated with BPH, with improvements seen in voiding and storage 
symptoms, maximum urinary flow rate and health-related quality of life in 
well-designed, 12-week trials. Silodosin was noninferior to tamsulosin in terms 
of improving LUTS associated with BPH. The efficacy of silodosin was maintained 
in 9-month extension studies and was also seen in a phase IV study conducted in 
a real-world setting. Silodosin was generally well tolerated and was associated 
with a low risk of orthostatic hypotension. Abnormal ejaculation was the most 
commonly reported adverse event, although few patients discontinued treatment 
with silodosin because of this adverse event. In conclusion, silodosin is a 
useful option for the treatment of LUTS associated with BPH.

